or global clock networks','','inherit','closed','closed','','343-revision-v1','','','2017-04-04 17:26:15','2017-04-04 17:26:15','',343,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/343-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(364,1,'2007-01-04 14:55:53','2007-01-04 14:55:53','[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nZ. Xu and K. L. Shepard, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/3.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Low-jitter active deskewing through injection-locked resonant clocking</a>\" IEEE Custom Integrated Circuits Conference, 2007.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full][av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nActive deskewing is an important technique for managing variability in clock distributions but introduces latency and power-supply-noise sensitivity to the resulting networks. In this paper, we demonstrate how active deskewing can be achieved with resonant distributions without introducing significant jitter. The prototype network operates at a nominal 2-GHz frequency in a 0.18μm CMOS technology with more than 25 pF/mm2 of clock loading.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n[/av_toggle_container]','Low-jitter active deskewing through injection-locked resonant clocking','','publish','open','open','','low-jitter-active-deskewing-through-injection-locked-resonant-clocking','','','2017-04-04 18:41:05','2017-04-04 18:41:05','',0,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/?p=364',0,'post','',0),(365,1,'2017-04-04 17:27:47','2017-04-04 17:27:47','','3','','inherit','open','closed','','3','','','2017-04-04 17:27:47','2017-04-04 17:27:47','',364,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/3.pdf',0,'attachment','application/pdf',0),(366,1,'2017-04-04 17:28:26','2017-04-04 17:28:26','Z. Xu and K. L. Shepard, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/3.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Low-jitter active deskewing through injection-locked resonant clocking</a>\" IEEE Custom Integrated Circuits Conference, 2007.','Low-jitter active deskewing through injection-locked resonant clocking','','inherit','closed','closed','','364-revision-v1','','','2017-04-04 17:28:26','2017-04-04 17:28:26','',364,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/364-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(367,1,'2007-01-04 14:44:35','2007-01-04 14:44:35','[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nI. Meric, V. Caruso, R. Caldwell, J. Hone, K. L. Shepard, and S. J. Wind, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/Hybrid-carbon-nanotube-silicon.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Hybrid carbon nanotube-silicon CMOS circuit</a>\" Journal of Vacuum Science and Technology B, 25, 6 (Nov/Dec, 2007), pp. 2577-2580\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full][av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nA hybrid technology is presented that combines carbon nanotube field-effect transistors (CNFET) with conventional, silicon-based complementary metal oxide semiconductor (CMOS) technology. The fabrication involves the chemical vapor deposition growth and optical characterization of carbon nanotubes, which are then transferred with lithographic precision onto a commercially fabricated CMOS substrate. In this manner, CNFET devices are fabricated on top of the interconnection network of the CMOS chip, providing a three-dimensional integration of active devices, “sandwiching” wiring, and passives. As a demonstration of this approach, a simple hybrid CNFET/CMOS inverter is fabricated and tested.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n[/av_toggle_container]','Hybrid carbon nanotube-silicon CMOS circuit','','publish','open','open','','hybrid-carbon-nanotube-silicon-cmos-circuit','','','2017-04-04 19:06:30','2017-04-04 19:06:30','',0,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/?p=367',0,'post','',0),(368,1,'2017-04-04 17:29:57','2017-04-04 17:29:57','','Hybrid carbon nanotube silicon','','inherit','open','closed','','hybrid-carbon-nanotube-silicon','','','2017-04-04 17:29:57','2017-04-04 17:29:57','',367,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/Hybrid-carbon-nanotube-silicon.pdf',0,'attachment','application/pdf',0),(369,1,'2017-04-04 17:30:37','2017-04-04 17:30:37','I. Meric, V. Caruso, R. Caldwell, J. Hone, K. L. Shepard, and S. J. Wind, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/Hybrid-carbon-nanotube-silicon.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Hybrid carbon nanotube-silicon CMOS circuit</a>\" Journal of Vacuum Science and Technology B, 25, 6 (Nov/Dec, 2007), pp. 2577-2580','Hybrid carbon nanotube-silicon CMOS circuit','','inherit','closed','closed','','367-revision-v1','','','2017-04-04 17:30:37','2017-04-04 17:30:37','',367,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/367-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(370,1,'2007-01-04 14:33:54','2007-01-04 14:33:54','[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nT.-C. Huang, S. Sorgenfrei, K. L. Shepard, P. Gong, and R. Levicky, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/6.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">A CMOS array sensor for sub-800-ps time-resolved fluorescence detection</a>\" IEEE Custom Integrated Circuits Conference, 2007.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full][av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nThis paper describes the design of an active CMOS sensor array for fluorescence applications which enables timegated, time-resolved fluorescence spectroscopy. The 64 x 64 array is sensitive to photon densities as low as 8 x 106 photons/ cm2 with 64-point averaging and, through a differential pixel design, has a measured impulse response of better than 800 ps. Applications include both active microarrays and high-frame-rate imagers for fluorescence lifetime imaging microscopy.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n\r\n[/av_toggle_container]','A CMOS array sensor for sub-800-ps time-resolved fluorescence detection','','publish','open','open','','a-cmos-array-sensor-for-sub-800-ps-time-resolved-fluorescence-detection','','','2017-04-04 18:45:07','2017-04-04 18:45:07','',0,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/?p=370',0,'post','',0),(371,1,'2017-04-04 17:33:11','2017-04-04 17:33:11','','6','','inherit','open','closed','','6','','','2017-04-04 17:33:11','2017-04-04 17:33:11','',370,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/6.pdf',0,'attachment','application/pdf',0),(372,1,'2017-04-04 17:34:05','2017-04-04 17:34:05','T.-C. Huang, S. Sorgenfrei, K. L. Shepard, P. Gong, and R. Levicky, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/6.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">A CMOS array sensor for sub-800-ps time-resolved fluorescence detection</a>\" IEEE Custom Integrated Circuits Conference, 2007.','A CMOS array sensor for sub-800-ps time-resolved fluorescence detection','','inherit','closed','closed','','370-revision-v1','','','2017-04-04 17:34:05','2017-04-04 17:34:05','',370,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/370-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(373,1,'2007-01-04 14:22:23','2007-01-04 14:22:23','[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nP. M. Levine, P. Gong, K. L. Shepard, and R. Levicky, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/7.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Active CMOS array for electrochemical sensing of biomolecules</a>\" IEEE Custom Integrated Circuits Conference, 2007.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full][av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nWe describe the design of a 4Å~4 active sensor array for multiplexed electrochemical biomolecular detection in a 0.25- μm-CMOS process. Integrated potentiostats sense the current flowing through the on-chip Au electrodes that result from reactions occurring at the chip surface. Preliminary experimental results include cyclic voltammetry of several redox species and application to DNA probe coverage characterization.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n[/av_toggle_container]','Active CMOS array for electrochemical sensing of biomolecules','','publish','open','open','','active-cmos-array-for-electrochemical-sensing-of-biomolecules','','','2017-04-04 19:04:08','2017-04-04 19:04:08','',0,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/?p=373',0,'post','',0),(374,1,'2017-04-04 17:35:16','2017-04-04 17:35:16','','7','','inherit','open','closed','','7','','','2017-04-04 17:35:16','2017-04-04 17:35:16','',373,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/7.pdf',0,'attachment','application/pdf',0),(375,1,'2017-04-04 17:36:02','2017-04-04 17:36:02','P. M. Levine, P. Gong, K. L. Shepard, and R. Levicky, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/7.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Active CMOS array for electrochemical sensing of biomolecules</a>\" IEEE Custom Integrated Circuits Conference, 2007.','Active CMOS array for electrochemical sensing of biomolecules','','inherit','closed','closed','','373-revision-v1','','','2017-04-04 17:36:02','2017-04-04 17:36:02','',373,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/373-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(376,1,'2007-01-04 14:15:21','2007-01-04 14:15:21','[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nK. A. Jenkins, K. L. Shepard, and Zheng Xu, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/8.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">On-chip circuit for measuring period jitter and skew of clock distribution networks</a>\" IEEE Custom Integrated Circuits Conference, 2007.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full][av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nA circuit for on-chip measurement of period jitter and skew of clock distribution is described. The circuit uses a single latch and a voltage-controlled delay element. The circuit is evaluated in a stand-alone pad frame, where a jitter resolution of about 1 ps is demonstrated, and is incorporated in a 2 GHz clock distribution network to obtain on-chip period jitter and clock skew measurement.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n[/av_toggle_container]','On-chip circuit for measuring period jitter and skew of clock distribution networks','','publish','open','open','','on-chip-circuit-for-measuring-period-jitter-and-skew-of-clock-distribution-networks','','','2017-04-04 19:04:20','2017-04-04 19:04:20','',0,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/?p=376',0,'post','',0),(377,1,'2017-04-04 17:37:26','2017-04-04 17:37:26','','8','','inherit','open','closed','','8','','','2017-04-04 17:37:26','2017-04-04 17:37:26','',376,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/8.pdf',0,'attachment','application/pdf',0),(378,1,'2017-04-04 17:38:23','2017-04-04 17:38:23','K. A. Jenkins, K. L. Shepard, and Zheng Xu, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/8.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">On-chip circuit for measuring period jitter and skew of clock distribution networks</a>\" IEEE Custom Integrated Circuits Conference, 2007.','On-chip circuit for measuring period jitter and skew of clock distribution networks','','inherit','closed','closed','','376-revision-v1','','','2017-04-04 17:38:23','2017-04-04 17:38:23','',376,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/376-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(379,1,'2007-01-04 14:11:36','2007-01-04 14:11:36','[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nV. Wang and K. L. Shepard, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/9.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">On-chip transistor characterisation arrays for variability analysis</a>\" Electronics Letters, Vol. 43, No. 15, July, 19, 2007.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full][av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nefficiently and accurately characterise large, dense arrays of transistors for variability studies is designed. The prototype macro is used to perform current–voltage characterisation of a 2.8 mm2, 1600- transistor array with digital interfaces.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n[/av_toggle_container]','On-chip transistor characterisation arrays for variability analysis','','publish','open','open','','on-chip-transistor-characterisation-arrays-for-variability-analysis','','','2017-04-04 19:04:28','2017-04-04 19:04:28','',0,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/?p=379',0,'post','',0),(380,1,'2017-04-04 17:39:37','2017-04-04 17:39:37','','9','','inherit','open','closed','','9','','','2017-04-04 17:39:37','2017-04-04 17:39:37','',379,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/9.pdf',0,'attachment','application/pdf',0),(381,1,'2017-04-04 17:40:18','2017-04-04 17:40:18','V. Wang and K. L. Shepard, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/9.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">On-chip transistor characterisation arrays for variability analysis</a>\" Electronics Letters, Vol. 43, No. 15, July, 19, 2007.','On-chip transistor characterisation arrays for variability analysis','','inherit','closed','closed','','379-revision-v1','','','2017-04-04 17:40:18','2017-04-04 17:40:18','',379,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/379-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(382,1,'2007-01-04 14:00:30','2007-01-04 14:00:30','[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nD. E. Schwartz, E. Charbon, and K. L. Shepard, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/A-Single-photon-Avalanche-Diode.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">A single-photon avalanche diode imager for fluorescence lifetime applications</a>\" Symposium on VLSI Circuits, 2007, pp. 144-245.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full][av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nA 64-by-64-pixel CMOS single-photon avalanche diode (SPAD) imager for time-resolved fluorescence detection features actively quenched and reset pixels, allowing gated detection to eliminate pile-up nonlinearities common to most time-correlated single-photon counting (TCSPC) approaches. Reset Timing information is collected using an on-chip time-tocalb calibrated digital converter (TDC) based on a counter and a supply- interpolators regulated delay-locked loop (DLL).\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n[/av_toggle_container]','A single-photon avalanche diode imager for fluorescence lifetime applications','','publish','open','open','','a-single-photon-avalanche-diode-imager-for-fluorescence-lifetime-applications','','','2017-04-12 01:23:40','2017-04-12 01:23:40','',0,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/?p=382',0,'post','',0),(383,1,'2017-04-04 17:42:04','2017-04-04 17:42:04','','A Single-photon Avalanche Diode','','inherit','open','closed','','a-single-photon-avalanche-diode','','','2017-04-04 17:42:04','2017-04-04 17:42:04','',382,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/A-Single-photon-Avalanche-Diode.pdf',0,'attachment','application/pdf',0),(384,1,'2017-04-04 17:42:58','2017-04-04 17:42:58','D. E. Schwartz, E. Charbon, and K. L. Shepard, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/A-Single-photon-Avalanche-Diode.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">A single-photon avalanche diode imager for fluorescence lifetime applications</a>\" Symposium on VLSI Circuits, 2007, pp. 144-245.','A single-photon avalanche diode imager for fluorescence lifetime applications','','inherit','closed','closed','','382-revision-v1','','','2017-04-04 17:42:58','2017-04-04 17:42:58','',382,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/382-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(385,1,'2007-01-04 13:55:08','2007-01-04 13:55:08','[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nA. P. Jose and K. L. Shepard, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/11.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Distributed loss-compensation techniques for energy-efficient low-latency on-chip communications</a>\" IEEE Journal of Solid-State Circuits, Vol. 42, June, 2007, pp. 1415-1424.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full][av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nIn this paper, we describe the use of distributed loss compensation to provide nearly transmission-line behavior for long on-chip interconnects. Negative impedance converters (NICs) inserted at regular intervals along an on-chip line are shown to reduce losses from more than 1 dB/mm to less than 0.3 dB/mm at 10 GHz. Results are presented for a 14-mm 3-Gb/s on-chip double-data-rate (DDR) link in 0.18- m CMOS technology, with a measured latency of 12.1 ps/mm and an energy consumption of less than 2 pJ/b with a BER 10 14. This constitutes a factor-of-three improvement in power and a one-and-a-half-times improvement in latency over an optimally repeated RC line of the same wire width.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n[/av_toggle_container]','Distributed loss-compensation techniques for energy-efficient low-latency on-chip communications','','publish','open','open','','distributed-loss-compensation-techniques-for-energy-efficient-low-latency-on-chip-communications','','','2017-04-04 19:04:39','2017-04-04 19:04:39','',0,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/?p=385',0,'post','',0),(386,1,'2017-04-04 17:44:05','2017-04-04 17:44:05','','11','','inherit','open','closed','','11','','','2017-04-04 17:44:05','2017-04-04 17:44:05','',385,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/11.pdf',0,'attachment','application/pdf',0),(387,1,'2017-04-04 17:44:45','2017-04-04 17:44:45','A. P. Jose and K. L. Shepard, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/11.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Distributed loss-compensation techniques for energy-efficient low-latency on-chip communications</a>\" IEEE Journal of Solid-State Circuits, Vol. 42, June, 2007, pp. 1415-1424.','Distributed loss-compensation techniques for energy-efficient low-latency on-chip communications','','inherit','closed','closed','','385-revision-v1','','','2017-04-04 17:44:45','2017-04-04 17:44:45','',385,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/385-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(3