ion=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\nI. Meric, N. Baklitskaya, P. Kim, and K. L. Shepard, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/iedm_final_v5.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">RF performance of top-gated, zero-bandgap graphene field-effect transistors</a>,\" International Electron Devices Meeting, 2008.\n[/av_textblock]\n[/av_one_full]\n\n[av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\nWe present the first experimental high-frequency measurements of graphene field-effect transistors (GFETs), demonstrating an fT of 14.7 GHz for a 500-nm-length device. We also present detailed measurement and analysis of velocity saturation in GFETs, demonstrating the potential for velocities approaching 108 cm/sec and the effect of an ambipolar channel on current-voltage characteristics.\n[/av_toggle]\n\n[/av_toggle_container]','RF performance of top-gated, zero-bandgap graphene field-effect transistors','','inherit','closed','closed','','391-autosave-v1','','','2017-04-04 19:38:39','2017-04-04 19:38:39','',391,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/391-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(397,1,'2017-04-04 18:26:15','2017-04-04 18:26:15','[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nI. Meric, N. Baklitskaya, P. Kim, and K. L. Shepard, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/iedm_final_v5.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">RF performance of top-gated, zero-bandgap graphene field-effect transistors</a>,\" International Electron Devices Meeting, 2008.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n[/av_one_full]\r\n\r\n[av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nWe present the first experimental high-frequency measurements of graphene field-effect transistors (GFETs), demonstrating an fT of 14.7 GHz for a 500-nm-length device. We also present detailed measurement and analysis of velocity saturation in GFETs, demonstrating the potential for velocities approaching 108 cm/sec and the effect of an ambipolar channel on current-voltage characteristics.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n\r\n[/av_toggle_container]','RF performance of top-gated, zero-bandgap graphene field-effect transistors','','inherit','closed','closed','','391-revision-v1','','','2017-04-04 18:26:15','2017-04-04 18:26:15','',391,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/391-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(398,1,'2017-04-04 18:27:34','2017-04-04 18:27:34','[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nK. L. Shepard and D. N. Maynard,<b> \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/Variability-and-yield-improvement.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Variability and yield improvements: rules, models, and characterization</a>\"</b> International Conference on Computer-Aided Design, 2006.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nYield and variability are becoming detractors for successful design in sub-90 nm process technologies. We consider the fundamental lithography and process issues that are driving variability and yield and the role of design rules in future processes. We\r\nexamine the importance of layout-aware modeling and layout regularity, including advantages and cost. Characterization structures for examining the electrical effects of device-level variability are discussed as well as circuit techniques for mitigating variability and yield challenges.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n\r\n[/av_toggle_container]','Variability and yield improvements: rules, models, and characterization','','inherit','closed','closed','','333-revision-v1','','','2017-04-04 18:27:34','2017-04-04 18:27:34','',333,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/333-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(399,1,'2017-04-04 18:29:01','2017-04-04 18:29:01','[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nG. Patounakis, K. L. Shepard, and R. Levicky, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/13.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Active CMOS array sensor for time-resolved fluorescence detection</a>\" IEEE Journal of Solid-State Circuits, November, 2006\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nSurface-based sensing assays based on fluorescence-based detection have become commonplace for both environmental and biomedical diagnostics. Traditional array scanners are expensive, large, and complex instruments. This paper describes the design of an active CMOS biosensor substrate for fluorescence-based assays that enables time-gated, time-resolved fluorescence spectroscopy without the need for an external reader. The array is sensitive to photon densities as low as 1 15 108 cm2, has a dynamic range of over 74 dB, and has subnanosecond timing resolution. Sensitivity is achieved through subsampling and averaging.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n\r\n[/av_toggle_container]','Active CMOS array sensor for time-resolved fluorescence detection','','inherit','closed','closed','','337-revision-v1','','','2017-04-04 18:29:01','2017-04-04 18:29:01','',337,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/337-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(400,1,'2017-04-04 18:30:00','2017-04-04 18:30:00','[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nY. W. Li, K. L. Shepard, and Y. P. Tsividis, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/14.pdf\">A continuous-time programmable digital FIR filter</a>\" IEEE Journal of Solid-State Circuits, November, 2006\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nIn this paper, we describe the design and implementation of a continuous time finite-impulse-response processor chain, which includes a 6-bit asynchronous ADC, an asynchronous digital core, and an 8-bit asynchronous DAC designed in TSMC 0.25- m technology. The continuous-time, discrete-amplitude systems combine benefits associated with analog and digital systems. Discrete-amplitude representations leverage the noise immunity and robustness of digital implementations. Continuous-time, nonsampled operation prevents aliasing and reduces the in-band quantization noise associated with the aliasing of subharmonic components. We present measurement results demonstrating an audio low-pass filter with a bandwidth of 6.0 kH.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n\r\n[/av_toggle_container]','A continuous-time programmable digital FIR filter','','inherit','closed','closed','','340-revision-v1','','','2017-04-04 18:30:00','2017-04-04 18:30:00','',340,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/340-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(401,1,'2017-04-04 18:30:53','2017-04-04 18:30:53','[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nS. C. Chan, K. L. Shepard, and P. J. Restle, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/15.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Distributed differential oscillators for global clock netwo</a><a href=\"https://www.bioee.ee.columbia.edu/downloads/2006/15.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">rks</a>\" IEEE Journal of Solid-State Circuits, September, 2006, pp. 2083-2094.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nThis paper presents a distributed differential oscillator global clock network where the clock capacitance is rendered resonant with a set of on-chip spiral inductors. The clock amplitude and clock phase are both uniform across the entire global distribution, making this design scalable and compatible with existing local clocking methodologies. The resonant network, combined with phase averaging of the distributed oscillator, provides high immunity to process-, voltage-, and temperature-variation induced timing uncertainty. Measurement results from a prototype design implemented in a 0.18- m CMOS technology show almost an order of magnitude less jitter and power than a traditional treedriven grid global clock distribution. On-chip measurement circuits are used to characterize the jitter on the test chip, while a simulation model is used to examine skew and higher-order resonances in the resonant clock network.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n\r\n[/av_toggle_container]','Distributed differential oscillators for global clock networks','','inherit','closed','closed','','343-revision-v1','','','2017-04-04 18:30:53','2017-04-04 18:30:53','',343,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/343-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(402,1,'2017-04-04 18:32:03','2017-04-04 18:32:03','[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\nG. Shen, N. Tercero, M. A. Gaspar, B. Varughese, K. Shepard, and R. Levicky, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/16.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Charging behavior of single-stranded DNA polyelectrolyte brushes</a>\" Journal of the American Chemical Society, Vol. 128, pp. 8427-8433, June, 2006.\n[/av_textblock]\n\n[av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\n[av_toggle title=\'Toggle 1\' tags=\'\']\nToggle Content goes here\n[/av_toggle]\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\nDNA monolayers are widely used in fundamental and applied genomics and are versatile experimental models for elucidating the behavior of charged polymers at interfaces. The physical behavior of these systems is to a large extent governed by their internal ionic microenvironment, which is investigated here for layers of end-tethered, single-stranded DNA oligonucleotides (DNA brushes). Retention of counterions by the DNA brush manifests as lowered susceptibility of the interfacial capacitance to external salt conditions. A physical model based on concepts adapted from polymer science was used to further elucidate the connection between monolayer organization and its charging behavior. The data indicate a reorganization of the monolayer with changes in ionic strength and strand coverage that is consistent with that expected for a polyelectrolyte brush. A method for electrochemical quantification of strand coverage, based on shift of reduction potential for redox counterions associated with the DNA monolayer, is also described. These results provide guidance for development of label free electrochemical diagnostics employing DNA monolayers and formulate a description of monolayer behavior within a polymer science framework.\n[/av_toggle]\n[/av_toggle_container]\n\n','Charging behavior of single-stranded DNA polyelectrolyte brushes','','inherit','closed','closed','','348-autosave-v1','','','2017-04-04 18:32:03','2017-04-04 18:32:03','',348,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/348-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(403,1,'2017-04-04 18:32:14','2017-04-04 18:32:14','[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nG. Shen, N. Tercero, M. A. Gaspar, B. Varughese, K. Shepard, and R. Levicky, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/16.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Charging behavior of single-stranded DNA polyelectrolyte brushes</a>\" Journal of the American Chemical Society, Vol. 128, pp. 8427-8433, June, 2006.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nDNA monolayers are widely used in fundamental and applied genomics and are versatile experimental models for elucidating the behavior of charged polymers at interfaces. The physical behavior of these systems is to a large extent governed by their internal ionic microenvironment, which is investigated here for layers of end-tethered, single-stranded DNA oligonucleotides (DNA brushes). Retention of counterions by the DNA brush manifests as lowered susceptibility of the interfacial capacitance to external salt conditions. A physical model based on concepts adapted from polymer science was used to further elucidate the connection between monolayer organization and its charging behavior. The data indicate a reorganization of the monolayer with changes in ionic strength and strand coverage that is consistent with that expected for a polyelectrolyte brush. A method for electrochemical quantification of strand coverage, based on shift of reduction potential for redox counterions associated with the DNA monolayer, is also described. These results provide guidance for development of label free electrochemical diagnostics employing DNA monolayers and formulate a description of monolayer behavior within a polymer science framework.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n\r\n[/av_toggle_container]','Charging behavior of single-stranded DNA polyelectrolyte brushes','','inherit','closed','closed','','348-revision-v1','','','2017-04-04 18:32:14','2017-04-04 18:32:14','',348,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/348-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(404,1,'2017-04-04 18:33:15','2017-04-04 18:33:15','[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nS. Rajapandian, K. L. Shepard, P. Hazucha, and T. Karnik, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/17.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">High-voltage power delivery through charge recycling</a>\" IEEE Journal of Solid-State Circuits, June, 2006, pp.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nIn this paper, we describe a technique for delivering power to a digital integrated circuit at high voltages, reducing current demands and easing requirements on power-ground network impedances. The design approach consists of stacking CMOS logic domains to operate from a voltage supply that is a multiple of the nominal supply voltage. DC–DC downconversion is performed using charge recycling without the need for explicit downconverters. Experimental results are presented for the prototype system in a 0.18- m CMOS technology operating at both 3.6 V and 5.4 V. Peak energy efficiencies as high as 93% are demonstrated at 3.6 V.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n\r\n[/av_toggle_container]','High-voltage power delivery through charge recycling','','inherit','closed','closed','','351-revision-v1','','','2017-04-04 18:33:15','2017-04-04 18:33:15','',351,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/351-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(405,1,'2017-04-04 18:34:02','2017-04-04 18:34:02','[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nA. P. Jose, G. Patounakis, and K. L. Shepard, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/18.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Pulse current-mode signalling for nearly speed-of-light intrachip communications</a>\" IEEE Journal of Solid-State Circuits, Vol. 41, April, 2006, pp. 772-780.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nIn this paper, we describe the design of on-chip repeater-less interconnects with nearly speed-of-light latency. Sharp current-pulse data transmission is used to modulate transmitter energy to higher frequencies, where the effect of wire inductance is maximized, allowing the on-chip wires to function as transmission lines with considerably reduced dispersion. A prototype 8-Gb/s serial link employing this pulsed current-mode signaling in a 0.18- m CMOS process is described and measured.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n\r\n[/av_toggle_container]','Pulse current-mode signalling for nearly speed-of-light intrachip communications','','inherit','closed','closed','','354-revision-v1','','','2017-04-04 18:34:02','2017-04-04 18:34:02','',354,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/354-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(425,1,'2017-04-04 18:54:13','2017-04-04 18:54:13','[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nS. Rajapandian, K. L. Shepard, P. Hazucha, and T. Karnik, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/17.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">High-voltage power delivery through charge recycling</a>\" IEEE Journal of Solid-State Circuits, June, 2006, pp.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nIn this paper, we describe a technique for delivering power to a digital integrated circuit at high voltages, reducing current demands and easing requirements on power-ground network impedances. The design approach consists of stacking CMOS logic domains to operate from a voltage supply that is a multiple of the nominal supply voltage. DC–DC downconversion is performed using charge recycling without the need for explicit downconverters. Experimental results are presented for the prototype system in a 0.18- m CMOS technology operating at both 3.6 V and 5.4 V. Peak energy efficiencies as high as 93% are demonstrated at 3.6 V.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n[/av_toggle_container]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full]','High-voltage power delivery through charge recycling','','inherit','closed','closed','','351-revision-v1','','','2017-04-04 18:54:13','2017-04-04 18:54:13','',351,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/351-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(409,1,'2017-04-04 18:44:11','2017-04-04 18:44:11','[av_one_full first  min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\n\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\nT.-C. Huang, S. Sorgenfrei, K. L. Shepard, P. Gong, and R. Levicky, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/6.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">A CMOS array sensor for sub-800-ps time-resolved fluorescence detection</a>\" IEEE Custom Integrated Circuits Conference, 2007.\n[/av_textblock]\n\n[/av_one_full][av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\n[av_toggle title=\'Toggle 1\' tags=\'\']\n[av_toggle title=\'Toggle 2\' tags=\'\']\n[/av_toggle_container]\n\n','A CMOS array sensor for sub-800-ps time-resolved fluorescence detection','','inherit','closed','closed','','370-autosave-v1','','','2017-04-04 18:44:11','2017-04-04 18:44:11','',370,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/370-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(410,1,'2017-04-04 18:39:58','2017-04-04 18:39:58','[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nZ. Xu and K. L. Shepard, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/3.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Low-jitter active deskewing through injection-locked resonant clocking</a>\" IEEE Custom Integrated Circuits Conference, 2007.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full][av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nActive deskewing is an important technique for managing variability in clock distributions but introduces latency and power-supply-noise sensitivity to the resulting networks. In this paper, we demonstrate how active deskewing can be achieved with resonant distributions without introducing significant jitter. The prototype network operates at a nominal 2-GHz frequency in a 0.18μm CMOS technology with more than 25 pF/mm2 of clock loading.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n[/av_toggle_container]','Low-jitter active deskewing through injection-locked resonant clocking','','inherit','closed','closed','','364-revision-v1','','','2017-04-04 18:39:58','2017-04-04 18:39:58','',364,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/364-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(411,1,'2017-04-04 18:42:41','2017-04-04 18:42:41','[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nI. Meric, V. Caruso, R. Caldwell, J. Hone, K. L. Shepard, and S. J. Wind, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/Hybrid-carbon-nanotube-silicon.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Hybrid carbon nanotube-silicon CMOS circuit</a>\" Journal of Vacuum Science and Technology B, 25, 6 (Nov/Dec, 2007), pp. 2577-2580\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nA hybrid technology is presented that combines carbon nanotube field-effect transistors (CNFET) with conventional, silicon-based complementary metal oxide semiconductor (CMOS) technology. The fabrication involves the chemical vapor deposition growth and optical characterization of carbon nanotubes, which are then transferred with lithographic precision onto a commercially fabricated CMOS substrate. In this manner, CNFET devices are fabricated on top of the interconnection network of the CMOS chip, providing a three-dimensional integration of active devices, “sandwiching” wiring, and passives. As a demonstration of this approach, a simple hybrid CNFET/CMOS inverter is fabricated and tested.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n[/av_toggle_container]','Hybrid carbon nanotube-silicon CMOS circuit','','inherit','closed','closed','','367-revision-v1','','','2017-04-04 18:42:41','2017-04-04 18:42:41','',367,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/367-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(412,1,'2017-04-04 18:45:07','2017-04-04 18:45:07','[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nT.-C. Huang, S. Sorgenfrei, K. L. Shepard, P. Gong, and R. Levicky, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/6.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">A CMOS array sensor for sub-800-ps time-resolved fluorescence detection</a>\" IEEE Custom Integrated Circuits Conference, 2007.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full][av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nThis paper describes the design of an active CMOS sensor array for fluorescence applications which enables timegated, time-resolved fluorescence spectroscopy. The 64 x 64 array is sensitive to photon densities as low as 8 x 106 photons/ cm2 with 64-point averaging and, through a differential pixel design, has a measured impulse response of better than 800 ps. Applications include both active microarrays and high-frame-rate imagers for fluorescence lifetime imaging microscopy.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n\r\n[/av_toggle_container]','A CMOS array sensor for sub-800-ps time-resolved fluorescence detection','','inherit','closed','closed','','370-revision-v1','','','2017-04-04 18:45:07','2017-04-04 18:45:07','',370,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/370-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(413,1,'2017-04-04 18:46:17','2017-04-04 18:46:17','[av_one_full first  min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\n\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\nP. M. Levine, P. Gong, K. L. Shepard, and R. Levicky, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/7.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Active CMOS array for electrochemical sensing of biomolecules</a>\" IEEE Custom Integrated Circuits Conference, 2007.\n[/av_textblock]\n\n[av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\n[av_toggle title=\'Toggle 1\' tags=\'\']\n[av_toggle title=\'Toggle 2\' tags=\'\']\n[/av_toggle_container]\n\n[/av_one_full]','Active CMOS array for electrochemical sensing of biomolecules','','inherit','closed','closed','','373-autosave-v1','','','2017-04-04 18:46:17','2017-04-04 18:46:17','',373,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/373-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(414,1,'2017-04-04 18:46:27','2017-04-04 18:46:27','[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nP. M. Levine, P. Gong, K. L. Shepard, and R. Levicky, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/7.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Active CMOS array for electrochemical sensing of biomolecules</a>\" IEEE Custom Integrated Circuits Conference, 2007.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nWe describe the design of a 4Å~4 active sensor array for multiplexed electrochemical biomolecular detection in a 0.25- μm-CMOS process. Integrated potentiostats sense the current flowing through the on-chip Au electrodes that result from reactions occurring at the chip surface. Preliminary experimental results include cyclic voltammetry of several redox species and application to DNA probe coverage characterization.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n\r\n[/av_toggle_container]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full]','Active CMOS array for electrochemical sensing of biomolecules','','inherit','closed','closed','','373-revision-v1','','','2017-04-04 18:46:27','2017-04-04 18:46:27','',373,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/373-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(415,1,'2017-04-04 18:47:32','2017-04-04 18:47:32','[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nK. A. Jenkins, K. L. Shepard, and Zheng Xu, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/8.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">On-chip circuit for measuring period jitter and skew of clock distribution networks</a>\" IEEE Custom Integrated Circuits Conference, 2007.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nA circuit for on-chip measurement of period jitter and skew of clock distribution is described. The circuit uses a single latch and a voltage-controlled delay element. The circuit is evaluated in a stand-alone pad frame, where a jitter resolution of about 1 ps is demonstrated, and is incorporated in a 2 GHz clock distribution network to obtain on-chip period jitter and clock skew measurement.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n\r\n[/av_toggle_container]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full]','On-chip circuit for measuring period jitter and skew of clock distribution networks','','inherit','closed','closed','','376-revision-v1','','','2017-04-04 18:47:32','2017-04-04 18:47:32','',376,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/376-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(416,1,'2017-04-04 18:47:44','2017-04-04 18:47:44','V. Wang and K. L. Shepard, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/9.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">On-chip transistor characterisation arrays for variability analysis</a>\" Electronics Letters, Vol. 43, No. 15, July, 19, 2007.','On-chip transistor characterisation arrays for variability analysis','','inherit','closed','closed','','379-autosave-v1','','','2017-04-04 18:47:44','2017-04-04 18:47:44','',379,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/379-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(427,1,'2017-04-04 18:55:46','2017-04-04 18:55:46','[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nV. Wang and K. L. Shepard, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/9.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">On-chip transistor characterisation arrays for variability analysis</a>\" Electronics Letters, Vol. 43, No. 15, July, 19, 2007.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nefficiently and accurately characterise large, dense arrays of transistors for variability studies is designed. The prototype macro is used to perform current–voltage characterisation of a 2.8 mm2, 1600- transistor array with digital interfaces.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n\r\n[/av_toggle_container]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full]','On-chip transistor characterisation arrays for variability analysis','','inherit','closed','closed','','379-revision-v1','','','2017-04-04 18:55:46','2017-04-04 18:55:46','',379,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/379-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(417,1,'2017-04-04 18:48:19','2017-04-04 18:48:19','[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nV. Wang and K. L. Shepard, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/9.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">On-chip transistor characterisation arrays for variability analysis</a>\" Electronics Letters, Vol. 43, No. 15, July, 19, 2007.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nefficiently and accurately characterise large, dense arrays of transistors for variability studies is designed. The prototype macro is used to perform current–voltage characterisation of a 2.8 mm2, 1600- transistor array with digital interfaces.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Toggle 2\' tags=\'\']\r\nToggle Content goes here\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n[/av_toggle_container]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full]','On-chip transistor characterisation arrays for variability analysis','','inherit','closed','closed','','379-revision-v1','','','2017-04-04 18:48:19','2017-04-04 18:48:19','',379,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/379-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(418,1,'2017-04-04 18:49:14','2017-04-04 18:49:14','[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nD. E. Schwartz, E. Charbon, and K. L. Shepard, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/A-Single-photon-Avalanche-Diode.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">A single-photon avalanche diode imager for fluorescence lifetime applications</a>\" Symposium on VLSI Circuits, 2007, pp. 144-245.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nA 64-by-64-pixel CMOS single-photon avalanche diode (SPAD) imager for time-resolved fluorescence detection features actively quenched and reset pixels, allowing gated detection to eliminate pile-up nonlinearities common to most time-correlated single-photon counting (TCSPC) approaches. Reset Timing information is collected using an on-chip time-tocalb calibrated digital converter (TDC) based on a counter and a supply- interpolators regulated delay-locked loop (DLL).\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n\r\n[/av_toggle_container]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full]','A single-photon avalanche diode imager for fluorescence lifetime applications','','inherit','closed','closed','','382-revision-v1','','','2017-04-04 18:49:14','2017-04-04 18:49:14','',382,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/382-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(419,1,'2017-04-04 18:50:07','2017-04-04 18:50:07','[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nA. P. Jose and K. L. Shepard, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/11.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Distributed loss-compensation techniques for energy-efficient low-latency on-chip communications</a>\" IEEE Journal of Solid-State Circuits, Vol. 42, June, 2007, pp. 1415-1424.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nIn this paper, we describe the use of distributed loss compensation to provide nearly transmission-line behavior for long on-chip interconnects. Negative impedance converters (NICs) inserted at regular intervals along an on-chip line are shown to reduce losses from more than 1 dB/mm to less than 0.3 dB/mm at 10 GHz. Results are presented for a 14-mm 3-Gb/s on-chip double-data-rate (DDR) link in 0.18- m CMOS technology, with a measured latency of 12.1 ps/mm and an energy consumption of less than 2 pJ/b with a BER 10 14. This constitutes a factor-of-three improvement in power and a one-and-a-half-times improvement in latency over an optimally repeated RC line of the same wire width.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n\r\n[/av_toggle_container]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full]','Distributed loss-compensation techniques for energy-efficient low-latency on-chip communications','','inherit','closed','closed','','385-revision-v1','','','2017-04-04 18:50:07','2017-04-04 18:50:07','',385,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/385-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(420,1,'2017-04-04 18:51:47','2017-04-04 18:51:47','[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nK. L. Shepard and D. N. Maynard,<b> \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/Variability-and-yield-improvement.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Variability and yield improvements: rules, models, and characterization</a>\"</b> International Conference on Computer-Aided Design, 2006.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full][av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nYield and variability are becoming detractors for successful design in sub-90 nm process technologies. We consider the fundamental lithography and process issues that are driving variability and yield and the role of design rules in future processes. We\r\nexamine the importance of layout-aware modeling and layout regularity, including advantages and cost. Characterization structures for examining the electrical effects of device-level variability are discussed as well as circuit techniques for mitigating variability and yield challenges.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n[/av_toggle_container]','Variability and yield improvements: rules, models, and characterization','','inherit','closed','closed','','333-revision-v1','','','2017-04-04 18:51:47','2017-04-04 18:51:47','',333,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/333-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(421,1,'2017-04-04 18:52:06','2017-04-04 18:52:06','[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nG. Patounakis, K. L. Shepard, and R. Levicky, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/13.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Active CMOS array sensor for time-resolved fluorescence detection</a>\" IEEE Journal of Solid-State Circuits, November, 2006\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nSurface-based sensing assays based on fluorescence-based detection have become commonplace for both environmental and biomedical diagnostics. Traditional array scanners are expensive, large, and complex instruments. This paper describes the design of an active CMOS biosensor substrate for fluorescence-based assays that enables time-gated, time-resolved fluorescence spectroscopy without the need for an external reader. The array is sensitive to photon densities as low as 1 15 108 cm2, has a dynamic range of over 74 dB, and has subnanosecond timing resolution. Sensitivity is achieved through subsampling and averaging.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n[/av_toggle_container]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full]','Active CMOS array sensor for time-resolved fluorescence detection','','inherit','closed','closed','','337-revision-v1','','','2017-04-04 18:52:06','2017-04-04 18:52:06','',337,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/337-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(422,1,'2017-04-04 18:52:41','2017-04-04 18:52:41','[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nY. W. Li, K. L. Shepard, and Y. P. Tsividis, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/14.pdf\">A continuous-time programmable digital FIR filter</a>\" IEEE Journal of Solid-State Circuits, November, 2006\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nIn this paper, we describe the design and implementation of a continuous time finite-impulse-response processor chain, which includes a 6-bit asynchronous ADC, an asynchronous digital core, and an 8-bit asynchronous DAC designed in TSMC 0.25- m technology. The continuous-time, discrete-amplitude systems combine benefits associated with analog and digital systems. Discrete-amplitude representations leverage the noise immunity and robustness of digital implementations. Continuous-time, nonsampled operation prevents aliasing and reduces the in-band quantization noise associated with the aliasing of subharmonic components. We present measurement results demonstrating an audio low-pass filter with a bandwidth of 6.0 kH.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n[/av_toggle_container]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full]','A continuous-time programmable digital FIR filter','','inherit','closed','closed','','340-revision-v1','','','2017-04-04 18:52:41','2017-04-04 18:52:41','',340,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/340-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(423,1,'2017-04-04 18:53:24','2017-04-04 18:53:24','[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nG. Shen, N. Tercero, M. A. Gaspar, B. Varughese, K. Shepard, and R. Levicky, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/16.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Charging behavior of single-stranded DNA polyelectrolyte brushes</a>\" Journal of the American Chemical Society, Vol. 128, pp. 8427-8433, June, 2006.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nDNA monolayers are widely used in fundamental and applied genomics and are versatile experimental models for elucidating the behavior of charged polymers at interfaces. The physical behavior of these systems is to a large extent governed by their internal ionic microenvironment, which is investigated here for layers of end-tethered, single-stranded DNA oligonucleotides (DNA brushes). Retention of counterions by the DNA brush manifests as lowered susceptibility of the interfacial capacitance to external salt conditions. A physical model based on concepts adapted from polymer science was used to further elucidate the connection between monolayer organization and its charging behavior. The data indicate a reorganization of the monolayer with changes in ionic strength and strand coverage that is consistent with that expected for a polyelectrolyte brush. A method for electrochemical quantification of strand coverage, based on shift of reduction potential for redox counterions associated with the DNA monolayer, is also described. These results provide guidance for development of label free electrochemical diagnostics employing DNA monolayers and formulate a description of monolayer behavior within a polymer science framework.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n[/av_toggle_container]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full]','Charging behavior of single-stranded DNA polyelectrolyte brushes','','inherit','closed','closed','','348-revision-v1','','','2017-04-04 18:53:24','2017-04-04 18:53:24','',348,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/348-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(424,1,'2017-04-04 18:53:38','2017-04-04 18:53:38','[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nS. C. Chan, K. L. Shepard, and P. J. Restle, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/15.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Distributed differential oscillators for global clock netwo</a><a href=\"https://www.bioee.ee.columbia.edu/downloads/2006/15.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">rks</a>\" IEEE Journal of Solid-State Circuits, September, 2006, pp. 2083-2094.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nThis paper presents a distributed differential oscillator global clock network where the clock capacitance is rendered resonant with a set of on-chip spiral inductors. The clock amplitude and clock phase are both uniform across the entire global distribution, making this design scalable and compatible with existing local clocking methodologies. The resonant network, combined with phase averaging of the distributed oscillator, provides high immunity to process-, voltage-, and temperature-variation induced timing uncertainty. Measurement results from a prototype design implemented in a 0.18- m CMOS technology show almost an order of magnitude less jitter and power than a traditional treedriven grid global clock distribution. On-chip measurement circuits are used to characterize the jitter on the test chip, while a simulation model is used to examine skew and higher-order resonances in the resonant clock network.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n[/av_toggle_container]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full]','Distributed differential oscillators for global clock networks','','inherit','closed','closed','','343-revision-v1','','','2017-04-04 18:53:38','2017-04-04 18:53:38','',343,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/343-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(426,1,'2017-04-04 18:54:42','2017-04-04 18:54:42','[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nA. P. Jose, G. Patounakis, and K. L. Shepard, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/18.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Pulse current-mode signalling for nearly speed-of-light intrachip communications</a>\" IEEE Journal of Solid-State Circuits, Vol. 41, April, 2006, pp. 772-780.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nIn this paper, we describe the design of on-chip repeater-less interconnects with nearly speed-of-light latency. Sharp current-pulse data transmission is used to modulate transmitter energy to higher frequencies, where the effect of wire inductance is maximized, allowing the on-chip wires to function as transmission lines with considerably reduced dispersion. A prototype 8-Gb/s serial link employing this pulsed current-mode signaling in a 0.18- m CMOS process is described and measured.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n[/av_toggle_container]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full]','Pulse current-mode signalling for nearly speed-of-light intrachip communications','','inherit','closed','closed','','354-revision-v1','','','2017-04-04 18:54:42','2017-04-04 18:54:42','',354,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/354-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(428,1,'2017-04-04 18:59:05','2017-04-04 18:59:05','[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nA. P. Jose, G. Patounakis, and K. L. Shepard, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/18.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Pulse current-mode signalling for nearly speed-of-light intrachip communications</a>\" IEEE Journal of Solid-State Circuits, Vol. 41, April, 2006, pp. 772-780.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full][av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nIn this paper, we describe the design of on-chip repeater-less interconnects with nearly speed-of-light latency. Sharp current-pulse data transmission is used to modulate transmitter energy to higher frequencies, where the effect of wire inductance is maximized, allowing the on-chip wires to function as transmission lines with considerably reduced dispersion. A prototype 8-Gb/s serial link employing this pulsed current-mode signaling in a 0.18- m CMOS process is described and measured.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n[/av_toggle_container]','Pulse current-mode signalling for nearly speed-of-light intrachip communications','','inherit','closed','closed','','354-revision-v1','','','2017-04-04 18:59:05','2017-04-04 18:59:05','',354,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/354-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(429,1,'2017-04-04 18:59:12','2017-04-04 18:59:12','[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nS. Rajapandian, K. L. Shepard, P. Hazucha, and T. Karnik, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/17.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">High-voltage power delivery through charge recycling</a>\" IEEE Journal of Solid-State Circuits, June, 2006, pp.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full][av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nIn this paper, we describe a technique for delivering power to a digital integrated circuit at high voltages, reducing current demands and easing requirements on power-ground network impedances. The design approach consists of stacking CMOS logic domains to operate from a voltage supply that is a multiple of the nominal supply voltage. DC–DC downconversion is performed using charge recycling without the need for explicit downconverters. Experimental results are presented for the prototype system in a 0.18- m CMOS technology operating at both 3.6 V and 5.4 V. Peak energy efficiencies as high as 93% are demonstrated at 3.6 V.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n[/av_toggle_container]','High-voltage power delivery through charge recycling','','inherit','closed','closed','','351-revision-v1','','','2017-04-04 18:59:12','2017-04-04 18:59:12','',351,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/351-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(430,1,'2017-04-04 18:59:19','2017-04-04 18:59:19','[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nG. Shen, N. Tercero, M. A. Gaspar, B. Varughese, K. Shepard, and R. Levicky, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/16.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Charging behavior of single-stranded DNA polyelectrolyte brushes</a>\" Journal of the American Chemical Society, Vol. 128, pp. 8427-8433, June, 2006.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full][av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nDNA monolayers are widely used in fundamental and applied genomics and are versatile experimental models for elucidating the behavior of charged polymers at interfaces. The physical behavior of these systems is to a large extent governed by their internal ionic microenvironment, which is investigated here for layers of end-t