9,1,'2017-04-04 20:27:31','2017-04-04 20:27:31','[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nI. Meric, C. Dean, A. F. Young, J. Hone, P. Kim, and K. L. Shepard, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/S23P02.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Graphene field-effect transistors based on boron nitride gate dielectrics</a>,\" International Electron Devices Meeting, 2010, pp. 23.2.1-23.2.4.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full][av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nGraphene field-effect transistors are fabricated utilizing single-crystal hexagonal boron nitride (h-BN), an insulating isomorph of graphene, as the gate dielectric. The devices exhibit mobility values exceeding 10,000 cm2/V-sec and current saturation down to 500 nm channel lengths with intrinsic transconductance values above 400 mS/mm. The work demonstrates the favorable properties of using h-BNas a gate dielectric for graphene FETs.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n\r\n[/av_toggle_container]','Graphene field-effect transistors based on boron nitride gate dielectrics','','inherit','closed','closed','','487-revision-v1','','','2017-04-04 20:27:31','2017-04-04 20:27:31','',487,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/487-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(490,1,'2010-01-04 20:20:38','2010-01-04 20:20:38','[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nS. Realov and K. L. Shepard, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/S28P02.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Random telegraph noise in 45-nm CMOS: analysis using an on-chip test and measurement system</a>,\" International Electron Devices Meeting, 2010, pp. 28.2.1-28.2.4.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full][av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nRTN measurements in 45-nm CMOS across device bias and geometry using an on-chip characterization system are reported. An automated methodology for extracting RTN levels, amplitude and dwell times is developed. Complex RTN magnitude is statistically modeled, and device size and bias parameter dependencies of the developed model are examined.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n\r\n[/av_toggle_container]','Random telegraph noise in 45-nm CMOS: analysis using an on-chip test and measurement system','','publish','open','open','','random-telegraph-noise-in-45-nm-cmos-analysis-using-an-on-chip-test-and-measurement-system','','','2017-04-04 21:15:24','2017-04-04 21:15:24','',0,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/?p=490',0,'post','',0),(491,1,'2017-04-04 20:30:17','2017-04-04 20:30:17','','S28P02','','inherit','open','closed','','s28p02','','','2017-04-04 20:30:17','2017-04-04 20:30:17','',490,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/S28P02.pdf',0,'attachment','application/pdf',0),(492,1,'2017-04-04 20:32:27','2017-04-04 20:32:27','[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nS. Realov and K. L. Shepard, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/S28P02.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Random telegraph noise in 45-nm CMOS: analysis using an on-chip test and measurement system</a>,\" International Electron Devices Meeting, 2010, pp. 28.2.1-28.2.4.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full][av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nRTN measurements in 45-nm CMOS across device bias and geometry using an on-chip characterization system are reported. An automated methodology for extracting RTN levels, amplitude and dwell times is developed. Complex RTN magnitude is statistically modeled, and device size and bias parameter dependencies of the developed model are examined.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n\r\n[/av_toggle_container]','Random telegraph noise in 45-nm CMOS: analysis using an on-chip test and measurement system','','inherit','closed','closed','','490-revision-v1','','','2017-04-04 20:32:27','2017-04-04 20:32:27','',490,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/490-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(493,1,'2010-01-04 20:01:44','2010-01-04 20:01:44','[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\' admin_preview_bg=\'\']\r\nR. M. Field, J. Lary, J. Cohn, L. Paninski, and K. L. Shepard, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/APPLAB9721211111_1.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">A low-noise, single-photon avalanche diode in standard 0.13 μm complementary metal-oxide-semiconductor process</a>,\" Applied Physcis Letters, 97, 211111 (2010).\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/field-apl-2010.tar.gz\">Data Download</a>\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full][av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nWe present the design and characterization of a single-photon avalanche diode SPAD fabricated with a standard 0.13 m complementary metal-oxide-semiconductor process. We have developed a figure of merit for SPADs when these detectors are employed in high frame-rate fluorescent lifetime imaging microscopy, which allows us to specify an optimal bias point for the diode and compare our diode with other published devices. At its optimum bias point at room temperature, our SPAD achieves a photon detection probability of 29% while exhibiting a dark count rate of only 231 Hz and an impulse response of 198 ps.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n[/av_toggle_container]','A low-noise, single-photon avalanche diode in standard 0.13 μm complementary metal-oxide-semiconductor process','','publish','open','open','','a-low-noise-single-photon-avalanche-diode-in-standard-0-13-%ce%bcm-complementary-metal-oxide-semiconductor-process','','','2017-04-12 01:22:55','2017-04-12 01:22:55','',0,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/?p=493',0,'post','',0),(494,1,'2017-04-04 20:33:52','2017-04-04 20:33:52','','APPLAB9721211111_1','','inherit','open','closed','','applab9721211111_1','','','2017-04-04 20:33:52','2017-04-04 20:33:52','',493,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/APPLAB9721211111_1.pdf',0,'attachment','application/pdf',0),(495,1,'2017-04-04 20:36:19','2017-04-04 20:36:19','[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nR. M. Field, J. Lary, J. Cohn, L. Paninski, and K. L. Shepard, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/APPLAB9721211111_1.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">A low-noise, single-photon avalanche diode in standard 0.13 μm complementary metal-oxide-semiconductor process</a>,\" Applied Physcis Letters, 97, 211111 (2010).\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_ful