s of externally coupled resonators to build dense sensor arrays without specialized fabrication techniques. The sensors in this work are constructed in a 6 4 array atop a 0.18μm CMOS active substrate, and mass sensitivity comparable to off-chip FBAR sensors is demonstrated.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n\r\n[/av_toggle_container]','FBAR-CMOS Oscillator Array for Mass-Sensing Applications','','inherit','closed','closed','','504-revision-v1','','','2017-04-04 21:27:31','2017-04-04 21:27:31','',504,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/504-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(507,1,'2010-01-04 15:27:45','2010-01-04 15:27:45','[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nC.J. Chen, C.A. Husko, I. Meric, K.L. Shepard, C.W. Wong, W.M. J. Green, Y.A. Vlasov, and S. Assefa, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/deterministic.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Deterministic tuning of slow-light in photonic crystal waveguides through the C and L bands by atomic layer deposition</a>,\" Applied Physics Letters, 96, 081107 (2010).\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full][av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nWe demonstrate digital tuning of the slow-light regime in silicon photonic-crystal waveguides by performing atomic layer deposition of hafnium oxide. The high group-index regime was deterministically controlled redshift of 14010 pm per atomic layer without affecting the group-velocity dispersion and third-order dispersion. Additionally, differential tuning of 11030 pm per monolayer of the slow-light TE-like and TM-like modes was observed. This passive postfabrication process has potential applications including the tuning of chip-scale optical interconnects, as well as Raman and parametric amplification.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n\r\n[/av_toggle_container]','Deterministic tuning of slow-light in photonic crystal waveguides through the C and L bands by atomic layer deposition','','publish','open','open','','deterministic-tuning-of-slow-light-in-photonic-crystal-waveguides-through-the-c-and-l-bands-by-atomic-layer-deposition','','','2017-04-04 21:30:13','2017-04-04 21:30:13','',0,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/?p=507',0,'post','',0),(508,1,'2017-04-04 21:28:28','2017-04-04 21:28:28','','deterministic','','inherit','open','closed','','deterministic','','','2017-04-04 21:28:28','2017-04-04 21:28:28','',507,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/deterministic.pdf',0,'attachment','application/pdf',0),(509,1,'2017-04-04 21:30:00','2017-04-04 21:30:00','[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nC.J. Chen, C.A. Husko, I. Meric, K.L. Shepard, C.W. Wong, W.M. J. Green, Y.A. Vlasov, and S. Assefa, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/deterministic.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Deterministic tuning of slow-light in photonic crystal waveguides through the C and L bands by atomic layer deposition</a>,\" Applied Physics Letters, 96, 081107 (2010).\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full][av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nWe demonstrate digital tuning of the slow-light regime in silicon photonic-crystal waveguides by performing atomic layer deposition of hafnium oxide. The high group-index regime was deterministically controlled redshift of 14010 pm per atomic layer without affecting the group-velocity dispersion and third-order dispersion. Additionally, differential tuning of 11030 pm per monolayer of the slow-light TE-like and TM-like modes was observed. This passive postfabrication process has potential applications including the tuning of chip-scale optical interconnects, as well as Raman and parametric amplification.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n\r\n[/av_toggle_container]','Deterministic tuning of slow-light in photonic crystal waveguides through the C and L bands by atomic layer deposition','','inherit','closed','closed','','507-revision-v1','','','2017-04-04 21:30:00','2017-04-04 21:30:00','',507,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/507-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(510,1,'2017-04-04 21:37:30','2017-04-04 21:37:30','[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\' admin_preview_bg=\'\']\r\nR. M. Field, J. Lary, J. Cohn, L. Paninski, and K. L. Shepard, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/APPLAB9721211111_1.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">A low-noise, single-photon avalanche diode in standard 0.13 μm complementary metal-oxide-semiconductor process</a>,\" Applied Physcis Letters, 97, 211111 (2010).\r\n\r\n<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/field-apl-2010.tar.gz\">Data Download</a>\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full][av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nWe present the design and characterization of a single-photon avalanche diode SPAD fabricated with a standard 0.13 m complementary metal-oxide-semiconductor process. We have developed a figure of merit for SPADs when these detectors are employed in high frame-rate fluorescent lifetime imaging microscopy, which allows us to specify an optimal bias point for the diode and compare our diode with other published devices. At its optimum bias point at room temperature, our SPAD achieves a photon detection probability of 29% while exhibiting a dark count rate of only 231 Hz and an impulse response of 198 ps.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n[/av_toggle_container]','A low-noise, single-photon avalanche diode in standard 0.13 μm complementary metal-oxide-semiconductor process','','inherit','closed','closed','','493-revision-v1','','','2017-04-04 21:37:30','2017-04-04 21:37:30','',493,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/493-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(511,1,'2017-04-04 21:40:21','2017-04-04 21:40:21','[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\' admin_preview_bg=\'\']\r\nR. M. Field, J. Lary, J. Cohn, L. Paninski, and K. L. Shepard, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/APPLAB9721211111_1.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">A low-noise, single-photon avalanche diode in standard 0.13 μm complementary metal-oxide-semiconductor process</a>,\" Applied Physcis Letters, 97, 211111 (2010).\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/field-apl-2010.tar.gz\">Data Download</a>\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full][av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nWe present the design and characterization of a single-photon avalanche diode SPAD fabricated with a standard 0.13 m complementary metal-oxide-semiconductor process. We have developed a figure of merit for SPADs when these detectors are employed in high frame-rate fluorescent lifetime imaging microscopy, which allows us to specify an optimal bias point for the diode and compare our diode with other published devices. At its optimum bias point at room temperature, our SPAD achieves a photon detection probability of 29% while exhibiting a dark count rate of only 231 Hz and an impulse response of 198 ps.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n[/av_toggle_container]','A low-noise, single-photon avalanche diode in standard 0.13 μm complementary metal-oxide-semiconductor process','','inherit','closed','closed','','493-revision-v1','','','2017-04-04 21:40:21','2017-04-04 21:40:21','',493,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/493-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(512,1,'2011-01-04 21:48:51','2011-01-04 21:48:51','[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nRosenstein, J. ; Bioelectron. Syst. Lab., Columbia Univ., New York, NY, USA ; Sorgenfrei, S. ; Shepard, K.L.\"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/Noise-and-bandwidth-performance-of-single-molecule-biosensors-IEEE-Xplore-Document.htm\" target=\"_blank\">Noise and bandwidth performance of single-molecule biosensors</a>,\" Custom Integrated Circuits Conference (CICC), 2011 IEEE\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full][av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nTechnological advances in fluorescent probes, solid-state imagers, and microscopy techniques have enabled biomolecular studies at the single-molecule level. Fluorescent techniques are highly specific but their bandwidth is fundamentally limited by the number of photons that can be collected. New electronic sensors including nanopores and nanotube field-effect transistors offer different tradeoffs between bandwidth and noise levels. Here, we discuss the performance of these direct solid-state interfaces and their potential for sensing single-molecule dynamics at shorter timescales.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n\r\n[/av_toggle_container]','Noise and bandwidth performance of single-molecule biosensors','','publish','open','open','','noise-and-bandwidth-performance-of-single-molecule-biosensors','','','2017-04-04 21:54:55','2017-04-04 21:54:55','',0,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/?p=512',0,'post','',0),(513,1,'2017-04-04 21:52:47','2017-04-04 21:52:47','','Noise and bandwidth performance of single-molecule biosensors - IEEE Xplore Document','','inherit','open','closed','','noise-and-bandwidth-performance-of-single-molecule-biosensors-ieee-xplore-document','','','2017-04-04 21:52:47','2017-04-04 21:52:47','',512,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/Noise-and-bandwidth-performance-of-single-molecule-biosensors-IEEE-Xplore-Document.htm',0,'attachment','text/html',0),(514,1,'2017-04-04 21:54:32','2017-04-04 21:54:32','[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nRosenstein, J. ; Bioelectron. Syst. Lab., Columbia Univ., New York, NY, USA ; Sorgenfrei, S. ; Shepard, K.L.\"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/Noise-and-bandwidth-performance-of-single-molecule-biosensors-IEEE-Xplore-Document.htm\" target=\"_blank\">Noise and bandwidth performance of single-molecule biosensors</a>,\" Custom Integrated Circuits Conference (CICC), 2011 IEEE\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full][av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nTechnological advances in fluorescent probes, solid-state imagers, and microscopy techniques have enabled biomolecular studies at the single-molecule level. Fluorescent techniques are highly specific but their bandwidth is fundamentally limited by the number of photons that can be collected. New electronic sensors including nanopores and nanotube field-effect transistors offer different tradeoffs between bandwidth and noise levels. Here, we discuss the performance of these direct solid-state interfaces and their potential for sensing single-molecule dynamics at shorter timescales.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n\r\n[/av_toggle_container]','Noise and bandwidth performance of single-molecule biosensors','','inherit','closed','closed','','512-revision-v1','','','2017-04-04 21:54:32','2017-04-04 21:54:32','',512,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/512-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(572,1,'2017-04-05 10:28:00','2017-04-05 10:28:00','[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\' admin_preview_bg=\'\']\r\nS. Realov and K. L. Shepard, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/RealovShepardVLSI2011.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">On-Chip Combined C-V/I-V Transistor Characterization System in 45-nm CMOS</a>,\" Symposium on VLSI Circuits, 2011.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full][av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nAn on-chip transistor characterization system for combined C-V/I-V characterization is presented. Capacitance measurement uses a quasi-static charged-based measurement technique with atto-Farad resolution. Random and systematic variability in device I-V and C-V characteristics is studied. The random variability in intrinsic gate capacitance is shown to exhibit Pelgrom scaling. Correlation between I-V and C-V measurements is used to identify systematic channel-length variation gradients in a device array.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n[/av_toggle_container]','On-Chip Combined C-V/I-V Transistor Characterization System in 45-nm CMOS','','inherit','closed','closed','','558-revision-v1','','','2017-04-05 10:28:00','2017-04-05 10:28:00','',558,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/558-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(573,1,'2017-04-05 10:32:34','2017-04-05 10:32:34','','cicc_jacob','','inherit','open','closed','','cicc_jacob','','','2017-04-05 10:32:34','2017-04-05 10:32:34','',541,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/cicc_jacob.pdf',0,'attachment','application/pdf',0),(516,1,'2011-01-04 21:45:05','2011-01-04 21:45:05','[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nRosenstein, J.; Ray, V.; Drndic, M.; Shepard, K.L.; \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/rosenstein_transducers2011.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Nanopore DNA sensors in CMOS with on-chip low-noise preamplifiers</a>,\" Solid-State Sensors, Actuators, and Microsystems Conference (Transducers), 2011.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full][av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nTechnological advances in fluorescent probes, solid-state imagers, and microscopy techniques have enabled biomolecular studies at the single-molecule level. Fluorescent techniques are highly specific but their bandwidth is fundamentally limited by the number of photons that can be collected. New electronic sensors including nanopores and nanotube field-effect transistors offer different tradeoffs between bandwidth and noise levels. Here, we discuss the performance of these direct solid-state interfaces and their potential for sensing single-molecule dynamics at shorter timescales.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n\r\n[/av_toggle_container]','Nanopore DNA sensors in CMOS with on-chip low-noise preamplifiers','','publish','open','open','','nanopore-dna-sensors-in-cmos-with-on-chip-low-noise-preamplifiers','','','2017-04-04 21:58:47','2017-04-04 21:58:47','',0,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/?p=516',0,'post','',0),(517,1,'2017-04-04 21:56:05','2017-04-04 21:56:05','','rosenstein_transducers2011','','inherit','open','closed','','rosenstein_transducers2011','','','2017-04-04 21:56:05','2017-04-04 21:56:05','',516,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/rosenstein_transducers2011.pdf',0,'attachment','application/pdf',0),(518,1,'2017-04-04 21:58:38','2017-04-04 21:58:38','[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nRosenstein, J.; Ray, V.; Drndic, M.; Shepard, K.L.; \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/rosenstein_transducers2011.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Nanopore DNA sensors in CMOS with on-chip low-noise preamplifiers</a>,\" Solid-State Sensors, Actuators, and Microsystems Conference (Transducers), 2011.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full][av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nTechnological advances in fluorescent probes, solid-state imagers, and microscopy techniques have enabled biomolecular studies at the single-molecule level. Fluorescent techniques are highly specific but their bandwidth is fundamentally limited by the number of photons that can be collected. New electronic sensors including nanopores and nanotube field-effect transistors offer different tradeoffs between bandwidth and noise levels. Here, we discuss the performance of these direct solid-state interfaces and their potential for sensing single-molecule dynamics at shorter timescales.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n\r\n[/av_toggle_container]','Nanopore DNA sensors in CMOS with on-chip low-noise preamplifiers','','inherit','closed','closed','','516-revision-v1','','','2017-04-04 21:58:38','2017-04-04 21:58:38','',516,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/516-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(519,1,'2011-01-04 20:11:48','2011-01-04 20:11:48','[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nRosenstein, J.; Ray, V.; Drndic, M.; Shepard, K.L.; \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/rosenstein_lissa2011.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Solid-state nanopores integrated with low-noise preamplifiers for high-bandwidth DNA analysis</a>,\" IEEE/NIH Life Science Systems and Applications Workshop (LiSSA), 2011.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full][av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nNanopore sensing platforms have been limited in bandwidth and noise performance by the use of external measurement electronics with significant parasitic impedances. In this work, we describe progress toward integrating detection electronics with solid-state nanopore sensors. This new platform for high-bandwidth single molecule electrochemical DNA analysis includes a low-noise 8-channel 0.13µm CMOS preamplifier with integrated Ag/AgCl microelectrodes. We also demonstrate monolithic integration of solid-state nanopores in the amplifier chip. This arrangement provides an opportunity to extend the useful bandwidth of nanopore sensors by a factor of ten or more.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n\r\n[/av_toggle_container]','Solid-state nanopores integrated with low-noise preamplifiers for high-bandwidth DNA analysis','','publish','open','open','','solid-state-nanopores-integrated-with-low-noise-preamplifiers-for-high-bandwidth-dna-analysis','','','2017-04-04 22:11:51','2017-04-04 22:11:51','',0,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/?p=519',0,'post','',0),(520,1,'2017-04-04 22:02:34','2017-04-04 22:02:34','','rosenstein_lissa2011','','inherit','open','closed','','rosenstein_lissa2011','','','2017-04-04 22:02:34','2017-04-04 22:02:34','',519,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/rosenstein_lissa2011.pdf',0,'attachment','application/pdf',0),(521,1,'2017-04-04 22:11:39','2017-04-04 22:11:39','[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nRosenstein, J.; Ray, V.; Drndic, M.; Shepard, K.L.; \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/rosenstein_lissa2011.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Solid-state nanopores integrated with low-noise preamplifiers for high-bandwidth DNA analysis</a>,\" IEEE/NIH Life Science Systems and Applications Workshop (LiSSA), 2011.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full][av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nNanopore sensing platforms have been limited in bandwidth and noise performance by the use of external measurement electronics with significant parasitic impedances. In this work, we describe progress toward integrating detection electronics with solid-state nanopore sensors. This new platform for high-bandwidth single molecule electrochemical DNA analysis includes a low-noise 8-channel 0.13µm CMOS preamplifier with integrated Ag/AgCl microelectrodes. We also demonstrate monolithic integration of solid-state nanopores in the amplifier chip. This arrangement provides an opportunity to extend the useful bandwidth of nanopore sensors by a factor of ten or more.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n\r\n[/av_toggle_container]','Solid-state nanopores integrated with low-noise preamplifiers for high-bandwidth DNA analysis','','inherit','closed','closed','','519-revision-v1','','','2017-04-04 22:11:39','2017-04-04 22:11:39','',519,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/519-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(522,1,'2011-01-04 19:55:01','2011-01-04 19:55:01','[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nG-H. Lee, Y-J. Yu, C. Lee, C. Dean, K. L. Shepard, P. Kim, and J. Hone, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/App-Phys-Letters.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Electron tunneling through atomically flat and ultrathin hexagonal boron nitride</a>,\" Applied Physcis Letters, 99, 243114 (2011).\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full][av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nElectron tunneling through atomically flat and ultrathin hexagonal boron nitride (h-BN) on gold-coated mica was investigated using conductive atomic force microscopy. Low-bias direct tunneling was observed in mono-, bi-, and tri-layer h-BN. For all thicknesses, Fowler-Nordheim tunneling (FNT) occurred at high bias, showing an increase of breakdown voltage with thickness. Based on the FNT model, the barrier height for tunneling (3.07 eV) and dielectric strength (7.94 MV/cm) of h-BN are obtained; these values are comparable to those of SiO<sub>2</sub>.\r\n[/a