,'','2017-04-05 08:42:41','2017-04-05 08:42:41','',525,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/525-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(531,1,'2011-01-04 19:44:10','2011-01-04 19:44:10','[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nN. Sturcken, M. Petracca, S. Warren, L. P. Carloni, A. V. Peterchev, and K. L. Shepard \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/IVR_CICC_revised.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">An Integrated Four-Phase Buck Converter Delivering 1A/mm2 with 700ps Controller Delay and Network-on-Chip Load in 45-nm SOI</a>\" IEEE Custom Integrated Circuits Conference, 2011.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nWe present a four-phase integrated buck converter in 45nm SOI technology. The controller uses unlatched pulse-width modulation (PWM) with nonlinear gain to provide both stable small-signal dynamics and fast response (~700ps) to large input and output transients. This fast control approach reduces the required output capacitance by 5X in comparison to a controller with latched PWM at similar operating point. The converter switches at 80MHz and delivers 1A/mm2 at 83% efficiency and 0.66 conversion ratio.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n[/av_toggle_container]','An Integrated Four-Phase Buck Converter Delivering 1A/mm2 with 700ps Controller Delay and Network-on-Chip Load in 45-nm SOI','','publish','open','open','','an-integrated-four-phase-buck-converter-delivering-1amm2-with-700ps-controller-delay-and-network-on-chip-load-in-45-nm-soi','','','2017-04-12 01:15:42','2017-04-12 01:15:42','',0,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/?p=531',0,'post','',0),(532,1,'2017-04-05 08:47:54','2017-04-05 08:47:54','','IVR_CICC_revised','','inherit','open','closed','','ivr_cicc_revised','','','2017-04-05 08:47:54','2017-04-05 08:47:54','',531,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/IVR_CICC_revised.pdf',0,'attachment','application/pdf',0),(1087,1,'2017-04-06 23:25:21','2017-04-06 23:25:21','[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nN. Sturcken, M. Petracca, S. Warren, L. P. Carloni, A. V. Peterchev, and K. L. Shepard \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/IVR_CICC_revised.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">An Integrated Four-Phase Buck Converter Delivering 1A/mm2 with 700ps Controller Delay and Network-on-Chip Load in 45-nm SOI</a>\" IEEE Custom Integrated Circuits Conference, 2011.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nWe present a four-phase integrated buck converter in 45nm SOI technology. The controller uses unlatched pulse-width modulation (PWM) with nonlinear gain to provide both stable small-signal dynamics and fast response (~700ps) to large input and output transients. This fast control approach reduces the required output capacitance by 5X in comparison to a controller with latched PWM at similar operating point. The converter switches at 80MHz and delivers 1A/mm2 at 83% efficiency and 0.66 conversion ratio.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n[/av_toggle_container]','An Integrated Four-Phase Buck Converter Delivering 1A/mm2 with 700ps Controller Delay and Network-on-Chip Load in 45-nm SOI','','inherit','closed','closed','','531-revision-v1','','','2017-04-06 23:25:21','2017-04-06 23:25:21','',531,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/531-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(533,1,'2017-04-05 08:49:42','2017-04-05 08:49:42','[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nN. Sturcken, M. Petracca, S. Warren, L. P. Carloni, A. V. Peterchev, and K. L. Shepard \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/IVR_CICC_revised.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">An Integrated Four-Phase Buck Converter Delivering 1A/mm2 with 700ps Controller Delay and Network-on-Chip Load in 45-nm SOI</a>\" IEEE Custom Integrated Circuits Conference, 2011.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\'][/av_one_full]\r\n\r\n[av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nWe present a four-phase integrated buck converter in 45nm SOI technology. The controller uses unlatched pulse-width modulation (PWM) with nonlinear gain to provide both stable small-signal dynamics and fast response (~700ps) to large input and output transients. This fast control approach reduces the required output capacitance by 5X in comparison to a controller with latched PWM at similar operating point. The converter switches at 80MHz and delivers 1A/mm2 at 83% efficiency and 0.66 conversion ratio.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n\r\n[/av_toggle_container]','An Integrated Four-Phase Buck Converter Delivering 1A/mm2 with 700ps Controller Delay and Network-on-Chip Load in 45-nm SOI','','inherit','closed','closed','','531-revision-v1','','','2017-04-05 08:49:42','2017-04-05 08:49:42','',531,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/531-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(534,1,'2011-01-04 19:40:42','2011-01-04 19:40:42','[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nS. Sorgenfrei, C.-Y. Chiu, M. Johnston, C. Nuckolls, and K. L. Shepard, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/Sorgenfrei_Nano_Letters.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Debye Screening in Single-Molecule Carbon Nanotube Field-Effect Sensors</a>,\" Nano Letters 11(9), pp. 3739-3743, 2011.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full][av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nPoint-functionalized carbon nanotube !eld-e\"ect transistors can serve as highly sensitive detectors for biomolecules. With a probemolecule covalently bound to a defect in the nanotube sidewall, two-level random telegraph noise (RTN) in the conductance of the device is observed as a result of a charged target biomolecule binding and unbinding at the defect site. Charge in proximity to the defect modulates the potential (and transmission) of the conductance-limiting barrier created by the defect. In this Letter, we study how these single molecule electronic sensors are a\"ected by ionic screening. Both charge in proximity to the defect site and bu\"er concentration are found to a\"ect RTN amplitude in a manner that follows from simple Debye length considerations. RTN amplitude is also dependent on the potential of the electrolyte gate as applied to the reference electrode; at high enough gate potentials, the target DNA is completely repelled and RTN is suppressed.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n\r\n[/av_toggle_container]','Debye Screening in Single-Molecule Carbon Nanotube Field-Effect Sensors','','publish','open','open','','debye-screening-in-single-molecule-carbon-nanotube-field-effect-sensors','','','2017-04-05 09:01:38','2017-04-05 09:01:38','',0,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/?p=534',0,'post','',0),(535,1,'2017-04-05 08:54:18','2017-04-05 08:54:18','','Sorgenfrei_Nano_Letters','','inherit','open','closed','','sorgenfrei_nano_letters','','','2017-04-05 08:54:18','2017-04-05 08:54:18','',534,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/Sorgenfrei_Nano_Letters.pdf',0,'attachment','application/pdf',0),(536,1,'2017-04-05 08:59:50','2017-04-05 08:59:50','[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nS. Sorgenfrei, C.-Y. Chiu, M. Johnston, C. Nuckolls, and K. L. Shepard, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/Sorgenfrei_Nano_Letters.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Debye Screening in Single-Molecule Carbon Nanotube Field-Effect Sensors</a>,\" Nano Letters 11(9), pp. 3739-3743, 2011.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full][av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nPoint-functionalized carbon nanotube !eld-e\"ect transistors can serve as highly sensitive detectors for biomolecules. With a probemolecule covalently bound to a defect in the nanotube sidewall, two-level random telegraph noise (RTN) in the conductance of the device is observed as a result of a charged target biomolecule binding and unbinding at the defect site. Charge in proximity to the defect modulates the potential (and transmission) of the conductance-limiting barrier created by the defect. In this Letter, we study how these single molecule electronic sensors are a\"ected by ionic screening. Both charge in proximity to the defect site and bu\"er concentration are found to a\"ect RTN amplitude in a manner that follows from simple Debye length considerations. RTN amplitude is also dependent on the potential of the electrolyte gate as applied to the reference electrode; at high enough gate potentials, the target DNA is completely repelled and RTN is suppressed.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n\r\n[/av_toggle_container]','Debye Screening in Single-Molecule Carbon Nanotube Field-Effect Sensors','','inherit','closed','closed','','534-revision-v1','','','2017-04-05 08:59:50','2017-04-05 08:59:50','',534,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/534-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(537,1,'2011-01-04 19:33:33','2011-01-04 19:33:33','[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nN. Lei, S. Ramamkrishnan, P. Shi, J. S. Orcutt, R. Yuste, L. C. Kam, and K. L. Shepard, \"<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/1741-2552_8_4_044003.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">High-resolution extracellular stimulation of dispersed hippocampal culture with high-density CMOS multielectrode array based on non-Faradaic electrodes</a>,\" J. Neural Eng. 8 (2011) 044003.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full][av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nWe introduce a method to electrically stimulate individual neurons at single-cell resolution in arbitrary spatiotemporal patterns with precise control over stimulation thresholds. By exploiting a custom microelectronic chip, up to 65 000 non-Faradaic electrodes can be uniquely addressed with electrode density exceeding 6500 electrodes mm−2. We demonstrate extracellular stimulation of dispersed primary hippocampal neuronal cultures using the chip at single-cell resolution.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n\r\n[/av_toggle_container]','High-resolution extracellular stimulation of dispersed hippocampal culture with high-density CMOS multielectrode array based on non-Faradaic electrodes','','publish','open','open','','high-resolution-extracellular-stimulation-of-dispersed-hippocampal-culture-with-high-density-cmos-multielectrode-array-based-on-non-faradaic-electrodes','','','2017-04-05 09:05:28','2017-04-05 09:05:28','',0,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/?p=537',0,'post','',0),(538,1,'2017-04-05 09:03:45','2017-04-05 09:03:45','','1741-2552_8_4_044003','','inherit','open','closed','','1741-2552_8_4_044003','','','2017-04-05 09:03:45','2017-04-05 09:03:45','',537,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/1741-2552_8_4_044003.pdf',0,'attachment','applicatio