ution for Very Large Scale Integrated Circuits,\" December 5, 2006.\r\n\r\nPatent No. US 7,103,522 B1 (<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/patent3.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">PDF</a>), \"Methods for Estimating the Body Voltage of Digital Partially Depleted Silicon-on-Insulator Circuits,\" September 5, 2006.\r\n\r\nPatent No. US 7,015,765 B2 (<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/patent4.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">PDF</a>), \"Resonant Clock Distribution for Very Large Scale Integrated Circuits,\" March 21, 2006.\r\n\r\nPatent No. US 6,453,444 B1 (<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/patent5.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">PDF</a>), \"Method for Extraction of Inductances in Integrated Circuits,\" September 17, 2002.\r\n[/av_textblock]','Patents','','inherit','closed','closed','','18-revision-v1','','','2017-04-07 16:40:45','2017-04-07 16:40:45','',18,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/18-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(1124,1,'2016-01-01 16:54:55','2016-01-01 16:54:55','The Brain Research through Advancing Innovative Neurotechnologies<sup>®</sup> (BRAIN) Initiative is aimed at revolutionizing our understanding of the human brain. By accelerating the development and application of innovative technologies, researchers will be able to produce a revolutionary new dynamic picture of the brain that, for the first time, shows how individual cells and complex neural circuits interact in both time and space. Long desired by researchers seeking new ways to treat, cure, and even prevent brain disorders, this picture will fill major gaps in our current knowledge and provide unprecedented opportunities for exploring exactly how the brain enables the human body to record, process, utilize, store, and retrieve vast quantities of information, all at the speed of thought.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.braininitiative.nih.gov/funding/fundedAwards.htm\" target=\"_blank\">Learn More</a>','Participating in four new BRAIN Initiative awards from NIH','','publish','open','open','','participating-in-four-new-brain-initiative-awards-from-nih','','','2017-04-11 16:43:30','2017-04-11 16:43:30','',0,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/?p=1124',0,'post','',0),(1125,1,'2017-04-07 17:06:48','2017-04-07 17:06:48','<a href=\"https://www.braininitiative.nih.gov/funding/fundedAwards.htm\" target=\"_blank\">Participating in four new BRAIN Initiative awards from NIH</a>','Participating in four new BRAIN Initiative awards from NIH','','inherit','closed','closed','','1124-revision-v1','','','2017-04-07 17:06:48','2017-04-07 17:06:48','',1124,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/1124-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(1126,1,'2016-01-01 15:09:32','2016-01-01 15:09:32','Columbia Engineering researchers have, for the first time, harnessed the molecular machinery of living systems to power an integrated circuit from adenosine triphosphate (ATP), the energy currency of life. They achieved this by integrating a conventional solid-state complementary metal-oxide-semiconductor (CMOS) integrated circuit with an artificial lipid bilayer membrane containing ATP-powered ion pumps, opening the door to creating entirely new artificial systems that contain both biological and solid-state components.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://engineering.columbia.edu/web/newsletter/spring_2016/introducing_biologically_powered_chip\" target=\"_blank\">Learn More</a>','Columbia Magazine article on biological electronics','','publish','open','open','','columbia-magazine-article-on-biological-electronics','','','2017-04-11 16:46:14','2017-04-11 16:46:14','',0,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/?p=1126',0,'post','',0),(1127,1,'2017-04-07 17:11:38','2017-04-07 17:11:38','<a href=\"http://engineering.columbia.edu/web/newsletter/spring_2016/introducing_biologically_powered_chip\" target=\"_blank\">Columbia Magazine article on biological electronics</a>','Columbia Magazine article on biological electronics','','inherit','closed','closed','','1126-revision-v1','','','2017-04-07 17:11:38','2017-04-07 17:11:38','',1126,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/1126-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(1128,1,'2015-12-09 17:12:42','2015-12-09 17:12:42','IEEE Spectrum - For the first time, researchers have developed a microchip that is powered by the same energy-rich molecules that fuel living cells, researchers say. This advance could one day lead to devices that are implanted within cells and harvest biological energy to operate.\r\n\r\nThe molecule adenosine triphosphate (<a href=\"http://spectrum.ieee.org/semiconductors/nanotechnology/rupturing-the-nanotech-rapture\">ATP</a>) stores chemical energy and is used inside cells to ferry energy from where it is generated to where it is consumed. The new microchip relies on enzymes known as sodium-potassium ATPases. These molecules break down ATP to release energy the enzymes use to pump sodium and potassium ions across membranes, generating an electrical potential during the process.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://spectrum.ieee.org/tech-talk/biomedical/devices/biopowered-chips-might-one-day-fit-inside-cells\" target=\"_blank\">Learn More</a>','Bio-Powered Chips Might One Day Fit Inside Cells','','publish','open','open','','bio-powered-chips-might-one-day-fit-inside-cells','','','2017-04-11 16:46:56','2017-04-11 16:46:56','',0,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/?p=1128',0,'post','',0),(1129,1,'2017-04-07 17:16:13','2017-04-07 17:16:13','<a href=\"http://spectrum.ieee.org/tech-talk/biomedical/devices/biopowered-chips-might-one-day-fit-inside-cells\" target=\"_blank\">Bio-Powered Chips Might One Day Fit Inside Cells</a> IEEE Spectrum','Bio-Powered Chips Might One Day Fit Inside Cells','','inherit','closed','closed','','1128-revision-v1','','','2017-04-07 17:16:13','2017-04-07 17:16:13','',1128,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/1128-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(1130,1,'2015-07-31 17:16:22','2015-07-31 17:16:22','This camera chip’s electrochemical imaging process is something like “taking a movie” over time, said Dr. Ken Shepard, a professor of electrical engineering and biomedical engineering and one of the researchers on the project. By recording the chemical activities of the bacteria, the researchers are able to learn more about the mechanisms that individual cells use to organize themselves into a community. Marshaling one billion individual P. aeruginosa cells into the colony formation pictured here, for instance, required a considerable amount of coordination on the part of the cells.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.nytimes.com/interactive/projects/cp/summer-of-science-2015/latest/bacteria-grid-quiz?smid=pl-share\" target=\"_blank\">Learn More</a>','What\'s That Science Thing: Bacteria Edition','','publish','open','open','','whats-that-science-thing-bacteria-edition','','','2017-04-11 16:52:11','2017-04-11 16:52:11','',0,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/?p=1130',0,'post','',0),(1131,1,'2017-04-07 17:17:25','2017-04-07 17:17:25','<a href=\"http://www.nytimes.com/interactive/projects/cp/summer-of-science-2015/latest/bacteria-grid-quiz?smid=pl-share\" target=\"_blank\">What\'s That Science Thing: Bacteria Edition</a>. New York Times','What\'s That Science Thing: Bacteria Edition','','inherit','closed','closed','','1130-revision-v1','','','2017-04-07 17:17:25','2017-04-07 17:17:25','',1130,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/1130-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(1132,1,'2014-10-01 17:17:33','2014-10-01 17:17:33','The Brain Research through Advancing Innovative Neurotechnologies<sup>®</sup> (BRAIN) Initiative is aimed at revolutionizing our understanding of the human brain. By accelerating the development and application of innovative technologies, researchers will be able to produce a revolutionary new dynamic picture of the brain that, for the first time, shows how individual cells and complex neural circuits interact in both time and space. Long desired by researchers seeking new ways to treat, cure, and even prevent brain disorders, this picture will fill major gaps in our current knowledge and provide unprecedented opportunities for exploring exactly how the brain enables the human body to record, process, utilize, store, and retrieve vast quantities of information, all at the speed of thought.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.braininitiative.nih.gov/funding/fundedAwards.htm\" target=\"_blank\">Learn More</a>','BRAIN initiative grants','','publish','open','open','','brain-initiative-grants','','','2017-04-11 16:53:51','2017-04-11 16:53:51','',0,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/?p=1132',0,'post','',0),(1133,1,'2017-04-07 17:18:58','2017-04-07 17:18:58','We are <a href=\"http://www.braininitiative.nih.gov/nih-brain-awards.htm\" target=\"_blank\">awarded</a>, along with colleagues at Caltech and Baylor, one of the first <a href=\"http://www.nih.gov/news/health/sep2014/od-30.htm\" target=\"_blank\">BRAIN initiative grants</a> to build a new nanophotonics platform for mapping the brain','BRAIN initiative grants','','inherit','closed','closed','','1132-revision-v1','','','2017-04-07 17:18:58','2017-04-07 17:18:58','',1132,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/1132-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(1134,1,'2014-07-15 17:19:13','2014-07-15 17:19:13','<span class=\"Red\">Ferric Semiconductor Inc.</span> makes EETimes \"Silicon 60\"! Founded in 2011, Ferric is developing innovative DC-to-DC conversion circuits based on a magnetic core inductor process that can be manufactured using CMOS back-end-of-line processes. This enables efficient, high-density on-chip or on-package power conversion at any process node. Ferric is working with foundry partner TSMC.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.eetimes.com/document.asp?doc_id=1323068&amp;page_number=4\" target=\"_blank\">Learn More</a>','Ferric makes EETimes \"Silicon 60\"!','','publish','open','open','','ferric-makes-eetimes-silicon-60','','\nhttp://www.eetimes.com/document.asp?doc_id=1323068&amp','2017-04-11 16:55:38','2017-04-11 16:55:38','',0,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/?p=1134',0,'post','',0),(1135,1,'2017-04-07 17:20:04','2017-04-07 17:20:04','<a href=\"http://www.eetimes.com/document.asp?doc_id=1323068&amp;page_number=4\" target=\"_blank\">Ferric makes EETimes \"Silicon 60\"</a>!','Ferric makes EETimes \"Silicon 60\"!','','inherit','closed','closed','','1134-revision-v1','','','2017-04-07 17:20:04','2017-04-07 17:20:04','',1134,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/1134-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(1136,1,'2014-03-10 17:20:13','2014-03-10 17:20:13','The Center for Infection and Immunity has been committed to research and service in global public heath since moving from the University of California to Columbia in 2001. The CII is directed by W. Ian Lipkin, MD, John Snow Professor of Epidemiology and Professor of Neurology and Pathology who has been named the “World’s Most Celebrated Virus Hunter”. BIOEE is participating in the new Center for Research in Diagnostics and Discovery.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://cii.columbia.edu/blog.aspx?cid=GMjPiJ\" target=\"_blank\">Learn More</a>','We are participating in the new Center for Research in Diagnostics and Discovery','','publish','open','open','','we-are-participating-in-the-new-center-for-research-in-diagnostics-and-discovery','','','2017-04-11 16:57:14','2017-04-11 16:57:14','',0,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/?p=1136',0,'post','',0),(1137,1,'2017-04-07 17:21:35','2017-04-07 17:21:35','<a href=\"http://cii.columbia.edu/blog.aspx?cid=GMjPiJ\" target=\"_blank\">We are participating in the new Center for Research in Diagnostics and\r\nDiscovery.</a>','We are participating in the new Center for Research in Diagnostics and Discovery','','inherit','closed','closed','','1136-revision-v1','','','2017-04-07 17:21:35','2017-04-07 17:21:35','',1136,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/1136-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(1138,1,'2014-02-01 17:21:40','2014-02-01 17:21:40','In a <a href=\"http://www.nature.com/ncomms/2014/140210/ncomms4256/full/ncomms4256.html\">study</a> published today in <a href=\"http://www.nature.com/ncomms/index.html\">Nature Communications</a>, a research team led by <a href=\"http://www.bioee.ee.columbia.edu/~shepard/\">Ken Shepard</a>, professor of electrical engineering and biomedical engineering at Columbia Engineering, and <a href=\"http://www.dietrichlab.com/\">Lars Dietrich</a>, assistant professor of biological sciences at Columbia University, has demonstrated that integrated circuit technology, the basis of modern computers and communications devices, can be used for a most unusual application—the study of signaling in bacterial colonies. They have developed a chip based on complementary metal-oxide-semiconductor (CMOS) technology that enables them to electrochemically image the signaling molecules from these colonies spatially and temporally. In effect, they have developed chips that “listen” to bacteria.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://engineering.columbia.edu/chips-listen-bacteria-0\" target=\"_blank\">Learn More</a>','Dan Bellin\'s new paper in Nature Communications','','publish','open','open','','dan-bellins-new-paper-in-nature-communications','','','2017-04-11 17:09:47','2017-04-11 17:09:47','',0,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/?p=1138',0,'post','',0),(1139,1,'2017-04-07 17:22:35','2017-04-07 17:22:35','<a href=\"http://engineering.columbia.edu/chips-listen-bacteria-0\" target=\"_blank\">Dan Bellin\'s new paper in Nature Communications</a>','Dan Bellin\'s new paper in Nature Communications','','inherit','closed','closed','','1138-revision-v1','','','2017-04-07 17:22:35','2017-04-07 17:22:35','',1138,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/1138-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(1140,1,'2014-03-01 17:22:37','2014-03-01 17:22:37','<div>A team of Columbia University professors has accomplished a state-of-the-art integration of computer circuit technology and biology. They have developed a chip that can listen to the communications of bacteria.</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div>The integrated circuit chip is similar to the ones used in regular computers or smart phones and measures electrochemical signals the bacteria use to \"talk to each other\".</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div>[swf src=\"http://en.cncnews.cn/player/39016/v.swf\" width=\"480\" height=\"400\"]</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<a href=\"http://en.cncnews.cn/news/v_show/39016_Chips_can_listen_to_bacteria.shtml\" target=\"_blank\">Learn More</a>','Chips can listen to bacteria: video from CNCnews.cn','','publish','open','open','','chips-can-listen-to-bacteria-video-from-cncnews-cn','','','2017-04-11 17:08:23','2017-04-11 17:08:23','',0,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/?p=1140',0,'post','',0),(1141,1,'2017-04-07 17:23:03','2017-04-07 17:23:03','<a href=\"http://en.cncnews.cn/news/v_show/39016_Chips_can_listen_to_bacteria.shtml\" target=\"_blank\">Chips can listen to bacteria: video from CNCnews.cn</a>','Chips can listen to bacteria: video from CNCnews.cn','','inherit','closed','closed','','1140-revision-v1','','','2017-04-07 17:23:03','2017-04-07 17:23:03','',1140,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/1140-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(1142,1,'2013-11-01 17:23:25','2013-11-01 17:23:25','Graphene has presented all sorts of barriers for efforts to apply the material to electronics. It lacks a band gap, so<a href=\"http://spectrum.ieee.org/nanoclast/semiconductors/nanotechnology/breakthrough-in-creating-a-band-gap-for-graphene-promises-huge-potential-for-electronic-applications\"> research has focused on engineering one into it</a>. Then even if you could engineer a band gap into the material, its challenging<a href=\"http://spectrum.ieee.org/nanoclast/semiconductors/nanotechnology/high-quality-graphene-could-be-produced-in-bulk\"> to manufacture</a> at a high quality and high volume.\r\n\r\nAnother big obstacle is that graphene does not lend itself to being stacked with other materials, something that could be important to <a href=\"http://spectrum.ieee.org/nanoclast/semiconductors/nanotechnology/lets-make-the-entire-chip-from-graphene\">making graphene ICs</a>. The reason is that electrical contacts have to be placed on the top surface of the graphene, making the layering of another material on top of those contacts complicated.\r\n\r\nNow researchers at Columbia University <a href=\"http://http//www.eurekalert.org/pub_releases/2013-10/cu-ntp102513.php\">have developed a way</a> to contact 2-D graphene from its 1-D side.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://spectrum.ieee.org/nanoclast/semiconductors/nanotechnology/engineers-make-electrical-contact-to-graphene-on-its-1-atom-thick-edge\" target=\"_blank\">Learn More</a>','Engineers Make Electrical Contact to Graphene on It\'s 1-Atom-Thick Edge','','publish','open','open','','engineers-make-electrical-contact-to-graphene-on-its-1-atom-thick-edge','','','2017-04-11 17:10:39','2017-04-11 17:10:39','',0,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/?p=1142',0,'post','',0),(1143,1,'2017-04-07 17:24:02','2017-04-07 17:24:02','<a href=\"http://spectrum.ieee.org/nanoclast/semiconductors/nanotechnology/engineers-make-electrical-contact-to-graphene-on-its-1-atom-thick-edge\" target=\"_blank\">Engineers Make Electrical Contact to Graphene on It\'s 1-Atom-Thick Edge</a>','Engineers Make Electrical Contact to Graphene on It\'s 1-Atom-Thick Edge','','inherit','closed','closed','','1142-revision-v1','','','2017-04-07 17:24:02','2017-04-07 17:24:02','',1142,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/1142-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(1144,1,'2013-11-01 17:01:25','2013-11-01 17:01:25','Columbia Engineering researchers have experimentally demonstrated for the first time that it is possible to electrically contact an atomically thin two-dimensional (2D) material only along its one-dimensional (1D) edge, rather than contacting it from the top, which has been the conventional approach. With this new contact architecture, they have developed a new assembly technique for layered materials that prevents contamination at the interfaces, and, using graphene as the model 2D material, show that these two methods in combination result in the cleanest graphene yet realized. The <a href=\"http://www.eurekalert.org/jrnls/sci\">study</a> is published in <em>Science</em> on November 1, 2013.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://engineering.columbia.edu/columbia-engineers-develop-new-device-architecture-2d-materials\" target=\"_blank\">Learn More</a>','New paper in Science on edge contacts to 2D materials.','','publish','open','open','','new-paper-in-science-on-edge-contacts-to-2d-materials','','','2017-04-11 17:11:46','2017-04-11 17:11:46','',0,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/?p=1144',0,'post','',0),(1145,1,'2017-04-07 17:25:10','2017-04-07 17:25:10','<a href=\"http://engineering.columbia.edu/columbia-engineers-develop-new-device-architecture-2d-materials\" target=\"_blank\">New paper in Science on edge contacts to 2D materials</a>.','New paper in Science on edge contacts to 2D materials.','','inherit','closed','closed','','1144-revision-v1','','','2017-04-07 17:25:10','2017-04-07 17:25:10','',1144,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/1144-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(1146,1,'2017-04-07 17:25:12','2017-04-07 17:25:12','<a href=\"http://spectrum.ieee.org/nanoclast/semiconductors/nanotechnology/engineers-make-electrical-contact-to-graphene-on-its-1-atom-thick-edge\" target=\"_blank\">Engineers Make Electrical Contact to Graphene on It\'s 1-Atom-Thick Edge</a>','Engineers Make Electrical Contact to Graphene on It\'s 1-Atom-Thick Edge','','inherit','closed','closed','','1142-autosave-v1','','','2017-04-07 17:25:12','2017-04-07 17:25:12','',1142,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/1142-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(1147,1,'2013-10-01 17:25:23','2013-10-01 17:25:23','<a href=\"http://www.arpa-e.energy.gov/?q=arpa-e-news-item/us-energy-department%E2%80%99s-arpa-e-announces-27-million-transformational-grid\" target=\"_blank\">New $3M award from ARPA-E</a>','New $3M award from ARPA-E','','publish','open','open','','new-3m-award-from-arpa-e','','','2017-04-11 17:14:43','2017-04-11 17:14:43','',0,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/?p=1147',0,'post','',0),(1148,1,'2017-04-07 17:25:58','2017-04-07 17:25:58','<a href=\"http://www.arpa-e.energy.gov/?q=arpa-e-news-item/us-energy-department%E2%80%99s-arpa-e-announces-27-million-transformational-grid\" target=\"_blank\">New $3M award from ARPA-E</a>','New $3M award from ARPA-E','','inherit','closed','closed','','1147-revision-v1','','','2017-04-07 17:25:58','2017-04-07 17:25:58','',1147,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/1147-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(1149,1,'2013-08-01 17:26:07','2013-08-01 17:26:07','An interdisciplinary team of researchers from Columbia University, led by <a href=\"http://www.bioee.ee.columbia.edu/~shepard/\">Ken Shepard</a>, professor of electrical engineering and biomedical engineering at Columbia Engineering and including <a href=\"http://www.columbia.edu/cu/chemistry/groups/cornish/\">Virginia W. Cornish</a>, Helena Rubinstein Professor of Chemistry, and <a href=\"http://www.dietrichlab.com/\">Lars Dietrich</a>, assistant professor of biological sciences, has won a prestigious $1 million three-year grant from the W. M. Keck Foundation to advance their research in combining biological components with solid-state electronics, creating new systems that exploit the advantages of both.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://engineering.columbia.edu/columbia-researchers-win-1-million-keck-award\" target=\"_blank\">Learn More</a>','Columbia Researchers Win $1 Million Keck Award!','','publish','open','open','','columbia-researchers-win-1-million-keck-award','','','2017-04-11 17:15:25','2017-04-11 17:15:25','',0,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/?p=1149',0,'post','',0),(1150,1,'2017-04-07 17:26:49','2017-04-07 17:26:49','<a href=\"http://engineering.columbia.edu/columbia-researchers-win-1-million-keck-award\" target=\"_blank\">Columbia Researchers Win $1 Million Keck Award!</a>','Columbia Researchers Win $1 Million Keck Award!','','inherit','closed','closed','','1149-revision-v1','','','2017-04-07 17:26:49','2017-04-07 17:26:49','',1149,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/1149-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(1151,1,'2017-04-07 17:26:58','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','Auto Draft','','auto-draft','open','open','','','','','2017-04-07 17:26:58','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/?p=1151',0,'post','',0),(1152,1,'2013-05-01 17:27:39','2013-05-01 17:27:39','A team of researchers at <a href=\"http://engineering.columbia.edu/\">Columbia Engineering</a> has used miniaturized electronics to measure the activity of individual ion-channel proteins with temporal resolution as fine as one microsecond, producing the fastest recordings of single ion channels ever performed. Ion channels are biomolecules that allow charged atoms to flow in and out of cells, and they are an important work-horse in cell signaling, sensing, and energetics. They are also being explored for nanopore sequencing applications. As the “transistors” of living systems, they are the target of many drugs, and the ability to perform such fast measurements of these proteins will lead to new understanding of their functions.\r\n\r\nLearn More:\r\n<a href=\"http://engineering.columbia.edu/researchers-perform-fastest-measurements-ever-made-ion-channel-proteins\" target=\"_blank\">Columbia Engineering</a>\r\n<a href=\"https://www.nsf.gov/news/news_summ.jsp?cntn_id=128151\" target=\"_blank\">National Science Foundation</a>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.sciencenewsline.com/summary/2013052015000027.html\" target=\"_blank\">Science Newsline</a>\r\n<a href=\"http://healthmedicinet.com/i/researchers-perform-fastest-measurements-ever-made-of-ion-channel-proteins/\" target=\"_blank\">Health Medicine Network</a>','News coverage for our fast ion channel measurements!','','publish','open','open','','news-coverage-for-our-fast-ion-channel-measurements','','','2017-04-11 17:16:22','2017-04-11 17:16:22','',0,'http://bioee.academicwebpages.com/?p=1152',0,'post','',0),(1153,1,'2017-04-07 17:29:01','2017-04-07 17:29:01','News coverage for our fast ion channel measurements!\r\n<a href=\"h